## Why Hardening, Not Just Patching
 
Patching closes known holes. Hardening removes the *configuration* an attacker relies on once they land — the flat local admin passwords, the credentials sitting readable in memory, the legacy protocols nobody turned off. In almost every breach report I read, the initial foothold is boring (phishing, an exposed RDP port), but the *escalation* is a hardening failure: pass-the-hash across identical local admins, NTLM relay to a domain controller, a Kerberoastable service account with a weak password.
 
This post is the checklist I actually apply to Windows Server 2019/2022 domain members and domain controllers. Every item includes the setting and a way to verify it. Test all of it in a pilot OU before you push it domain-wide — some of these controls break legacy agents (I learned that the hard way with LSA Protection).
 
---
 
## Lab / Environment Assumptions
 
- **Domain Controllers:** Windows Server 2019 or 2022, functional level 2016+
- **Members:** Windows Server 2019/2022
- **Tooling:** Group Policy Management Console (GPMC), RSAT, PowerShell as Domain Admin
- **Baselines:** Microsoft Security Compliance Toolkit (SCT) downloaded
- **Rule:** Pilot OU first, then rings — never straight to production
---
 
## 1. Start From a Microsoft Security Baseline
 
Don't hand-craft hundreds of registry values. Microsoft publishes hardened GPO baselines in the **Security Compliance Toolkit (SCT)** for each Windows Server version. Import them, then adjust for your environment rather than starting from a blank policy.
 
```powershell
# After downloading the Security Compliance Toolkit and the
# Windows Server 2022 baseline, import the GPOs:
.\Baseline-LocalInstall.ps1 -WindowsServerDC   # for domain controllers
.\Baseline-LocalInstall.ps1 -WindowsServerMember
```
 
Use the included **Policy Analyzer** tool to diff the baseline against your current GPOs so you can see exactly what will change before it hits users. The baseline gives you 80% of the hardening in one import — the items below are the high-value additions and the ones people most often miss.
 
