## 2. Enable LSA Protection (RunAsPPL)
 
The Local Security Authority (LSASS) holds credential material in memory. Running it as a **Protected Process Light** blocks tools like Mimikatz from reading it.
 
```powershell
New-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Lsa" `
  -Name "RunAsPPL" -Value 1 -PropertyType DWORD -Force
```
 
On Windows Server 2022 you can also enable it via GPO: **Computer Configuration → Administrative Templates → System → Local Security Authority → Configure LSASS to run as a protected process**.
 
> **Warning:** Anything that injects a DLL into LSASS — some MFA agents, EDR products, and VPN SSO clients — can break silently. Pilot this and confirm every third-party auth product is PPL-compatible before rolling out.
{: .prompt-warning }
 
Verify after reboot:
 
```powershell
Get-ItemProperty "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Lsa" -Name RunAsPPL
```
 
